\series bold
Symmetry properties of V
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
From the imposed symmetry 
\begin_inset Formula $V(\mathbf{r}-\mathbf{r}^{\prime})=V(\mathbf{r}^{\prime}-\mathbf{r})$
\end_inset

, we obtain
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
V_{\gamma\delta}^{\alpha\beta} & =\int d\mathbf{r}d\mathbf{r}^{\prime}\phi_{\alpha}^{*}(\mathbf{r})\phi_{\beta}^{*}(\mathbf{r}^{\prime})V(\mathbf{r}-\mathbf{r}^{\prime})\phi_{\gamma}(\mathbf{r}^{\prime})\phi_{\delta}(\mathbf{r}),\text{ }\mathbf{r}\leftrightharpoons\mathbf{r}^{\prime}\\
 & =\int d\mathbf{r}d\mathbf{r}^{\prime}\phi_{\alpha}^{*}(\mathbf{r}^{\prime})\phi_{\beta}^{*}(\mathbf{r})V(\mathbf{r}-\mathbf{r}^{\prime})\phi_{\gamma}(\mathbf{r})\phi_{\delta}(\mathbf{r}^{\prime})\\
 & =\int d\mathbf{r}d\mathbf{r}^{\prime}\phi_{\beta}^{*}(\mathbf{r})\phi_{\alpha}^{*}\left(\mathbf{r}^{\prime}\right)V(\mathbf{r}-\mathbf{r}^{\prime})\phi_{\delta}(\mathbf{r}^{\prime})\phi_{\gamma}(\mathbf{r})=V_{\delta\gamma}^{\beta\alpha}\text{ }_{\square}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Similarly, we can show that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\left(V_{\gamma\delta}^{\alpha\beta}\right)^{*} & =\int d\mathbf{r}d\mathbf{r}^{\prime}\phi_{\alpha}(\mathbf{r})\phi_{\beta}(\mathbf{r}^{\prime})V(\mathbf{r}-\mathbf{r}^{\prime})\phi_{\gamma}^{*}(\mathbf{r}^{\prime})\phi_{\delta}^{*}(\mathbf{r})\\
 & =\int d\mathbf{r}d\mathbf{r}^{\prime}\phi_{\delta}^{*}(\mathbf{r})\phi_{\gamma}^{*}(\mathbf{r}^{\prime})V(\mathbf{r}-\mathbf{r}^{\prime})\phi_{\delta}(\mathbf{r}^{\prime})\phi_{\alpha}(\mathbf{r})=V_{\beta\alpha}^{\delta\gamma}=V_{\alpha\beta}^{\gamma\delta}\text{ }_{\square}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In order to study the dynamics of this system, we solve for the time-evolution
 of the the system's reduced density matrix (rDM) through it's its equation
 of motion (EoM).
 The system's purely electronic reduced density matrix (rDM) is defined
 as 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{ba}^{\text{ee}}=\langle c_{a}^{\dagger}c_{b}\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 However, if one wishes to study superconducting systems, one must also
 account for the anomalous terms.
 For this, we introduce the Nambu spinor representation with doubling of
 degrees of freedom 
\begin_inset Formula $\check{c}_{a}=(c_{a}\,\,c_{a}^{\dagger})$
\end_inset

.
 The Nambu representation of the rDM, can then be written as the tensor
 product of this spinors for each of the spin combinations,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\rho_{ab}=\left(\begin{array}{cc}
\langle c_{b}^{\dagger}c_{a}\rangle & \langle c_{b}c_{a}\rangle\\
\langle c_{b}^{\dagger}c_{a}^{\dagger}\rangle & \langle c_{b}c_{a}^{\dagger}\rangle
\end{array}\right)=\left(\begin{array}{cc}
\rho_{ab}^{\text{ee}} & \rho_{ab}^{\text{eh}}\\
\rho_{ab}^{\text{he}} & \rho_{ab}^{\text{hh}}
\end{array}\right).\label{eq:rDM}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Directly from the (equal-time) fermionic anti-commutator properties, this
 terms relate to each other as 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{ab}^{\text{hh}}=-\rho_{ba}^{\text{ee}}+\delta_{ab}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{ab}^{\text{he}}=(\rho_{ba}^{\text{eh}})^{*}$
\end_inset

, but also 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{ab}^{\text{ee/hh}}=(\rho_{ba}^{\text{ee/hh}})^{*}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{ba}^{\text{eh/he}}=-\rho_{ab}^{\text{eh/he}}$
\end_inset

.
 Notice that, since the spin degree of freedom was not yet specified we
 are not yet restricting ourselves to typical 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

-wave spin-singlet superconductors, this is a general treatment.
 Our task now is then to solve the two distinct EoMs, for the purely electronic
 rDM 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{ab}^{\text{ee}}$
\end_inset

, which then determines the other two simple through their relations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Reduced density matrices equations of motion
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We start by solving for the purely electronic rDM equation of motions
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{d}{dt}\rho_{ab}^{\text{ee}}(t)=\left\langle \frac{dc_{b}^{\dagger}(t)}{dt}c_{a}(t)\right\rangle +\left\langle c_{b}^{\dagger}(t)\frac{dc_{a}(t)}{dt}\right\rangle ,
\end{equation}

\end_inset

in the Heisenberg picture of quantum mechanics, where the fermionic operators
 evolve accordingly to the Heisenberg equation.
 Therefore the rDM equation of motion reads
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{d}{dt}\rho_{ab}^{\text{ee}}=\left\langle \frac{i}{\hbar}[H,c_{b}^{\dagger}]c_{a}\right\rangle +\left\langle c_{b}^{\dagger}\frac{i}{\hbar}[H,c_{a}]\right\rangle .\label{eq:EM_rho}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where we have omitted the time dependency in the fermionic operators for
 compactness.
 This practice is done throughout the remaining work with no further mention.
 As shown in Appendix, given the equal-time fermionic anti-commutator properties
 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ c_{a},c_{b}^{\dagger}\right\} =\left\{ c_{b}^{\dagger},c_{a}\right\} =\delta_{ab}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ c_{a},c_{b}\right\} =\left\{ c_{b}^{\dagger},c_{a}^{\dagger}\right\} =0$
\end_inset

, each of the commutators are evaluated to
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
[H,c_{b}^{\dagger}] & =\bar{h}_{\alpha b}c_{\alpha}^{\dagger}+\frac{1}{4}\left(V_{\gamma b}^{\alpha\beta}-V_{b\gamma}^{\alpha\beta}\right)\left(c_{\alpha}^{\dagger}c_{\beta}^{\dagger}c_{\gamma}-c_{\gamma}c_{\beta}^{\dagger}c_{\alpha}^{\dagger}\right)\label{eq:Hcb}\\{}
[H,c_{a}] & =-\bar{h}_{a\alpha}c_{\alpha}+\frac{1}{4}\left(V_{\beta\gamma}^{\alpha a}-V_{\beta\gamma}^{a\alpha}\right)\left(c_{\alpha}^{\dagger}c_{\beta}c_{\gamma}-c_{\gamma}c_{\beta}c_{\alpha}^{\dagger}\right),\label{eq:Hca}
\end{align}

\end_inset

where we have hidden the summations on repeated indices using Einstein's
 notation.
 
