\begin_layout Standard
The main objective of this section is to derive the BCS gap equation from
 our Hartree-Fock-Bogoliubov approach with the additional generalization
 of allowing for a Zeeman field and spin orbit coupling, accounting not
 only for the self-consistent pairing but also the self-consistently induced
 magnetization and doping.
 However, we will not account for SOC effects as the analytical derivation
 is to convoluted and compare the analytical results only to the case when
 we set 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{R}=0$
\end_inset

 in the numerical case.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider the non-interacting Hamiltonian 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{0}$
\end_inset

 for an infinite nanowire in the presence of an external Zeeman field 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{\text{Z}}$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
H_{0}(k)=\sum_{s}c_{ks}^{\dagger}\left[(\epsilon_{k}-\mu)\delta_{ss^{\prime}}+V_{Z}\sigma_{z}\right]c_{ks^{\prime}},\label{eq:gap_H}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

with 
\begin_inset Formula $c^{\dagger}(c)$
\end_inset

 fermionic creation (annihilation) operators specified by its spin degree
 of freedom 
\begin_inset Formula $s=\uparrow/\downarrow$
\end_inset

 and momentum 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon_{k}$
\end_inset

 the respective spin independent (hence the 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{ss^{\prime}}$
\end_inset

) energy and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 the chemical potential.
 Once more, both 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 are Pauli matrices operating in their respectively spin and electron-hole
 subspaces the Hamiltonian.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One can reparametrizaze the onsite Hartree-Fock-Bogoliubov self-energy in
 the Wannier-Hubbard limit in Eq.(
\begin_inset Formula $\text{\ref{eq:Sigma}}$
\end_inset

) with the symmetries of Eq.(
\begin_inset Formula $\text{\ref{eq:rDM}}$
\end_inset

) in terms of the self-consistently induced magnetization 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta V_{\text{Z}}$
\end_inset

, doping 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta\mu$
\end_inset

 and pairing 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta$
\end_inset

 (assumed to be real) as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\boldsymbol{\Sigma}_{ii}=\left(\delta V_{\text{Z}}\left[\tau_{z}\otimes\sigma_{z}\right]-\delta\mu\left[\tau_{z}\otimes\sigma_{0}\right]\right)-\Delta\left[\tau_{y}\otimes\sigma_{y}\right].
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Flex Color Box
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
colback=black!5!white, colframe=black!5!white, breakable
\end_layout

\end_inset


\series bold
Self-energy matrix
\series default

\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\boldsymbol{\Sigma}=\left(\begin{array}{c|c||c|c}
\delta\mu+\delta V_{\text{Z}} &  &  & -\Delta\\
\hline  & \delta\mu-\delta V_{\text{Z}} & \Delta\\
\hline\hline  & \Delta & -\delta\mu-\delta V_{\text{Z}}\\
\hline -\Delta &  &  & -\delta\mu+\delta V_{\text{Z}}
\end{array}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

Comparing this form with Eq.(
\begin_inset Formula $\text{\ref{eq:Sigma}}$
\end_inset

), we can identify the diagonal and off-diagonal block respectively as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
-i\Delta\sigma_{y}=\textcolor{red}{-}U\left(\begin{array}{cc}
0 & \rho_{\uparrow\downarrow}^{\text{eh}}\\
\rho_{\downarrow\uparrow}^{\text{eh}} & 0
\end{array}\right)\quad\text{and}\quad\textcolor{red}{-}\delta V_{\text{Z}}\sigma_{z}-\delta\mu\sigma_{0}=\textcolor{red}{-\cancel{\frac{1}{2}}}U\left(\begin{array}{cc}
\rho_{\downarrow\downarrow}^{\text{ee}} & 0\\
0 & \rho_{\uparrow\uparrow}^{\text{ee}}
\end{array}\right)\label{eq:gapeqs}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where we start to omit the indices since they are all onsite terms.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us first focus on the pairing term and then on the normal one.
 Given that 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{\uparrow\downarrow}^{\text{eh}}=-\rho_{\downarrow\uparrow}^{\text{eh}}$
\end_inset

 the pairing term becomes even simpler reading just 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta=U\rho_{\uparrow\downarrow}^{\text{eh}}$
\end_inset

.
 The superconductive correlation 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{\uparrow\downarrow}^{\text{eh}}$
\end_inset

, which is being described in orbital space, can then be Fourier transformed
 into the momentum space as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\boldsymbol{\rho}_{ij} & =\frac{1}{N}\sum_{k}\langle\check{\boldsymbol{c}}_{k}^{\dagger}\otimes\check{\boldsymbol{c}}_{k}\rangle e^{\textcolor{red}{i}k(x_{j}-x_{i})}\label{eq:rho_k}
\end{align}

\end_inset

with 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 summed over the Brillouin zone and 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 the total number of sites in the system.
 Furthermore, one can express Eq.(
\begin_inset Formula $\text{\ref{eq:rho_k}}$
\end_inset

) in a Bogoliubov basis for the Cooper pairs such that the Hamiltonian block
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\boldsymbol{H}(k)=\boldsymbol{H}_{0}(k)+\boldsymbol{\Sigma}=\left(\begin{array}{cc}
\tilde{\epsilon}_{k}+\tilde{V}_{\text{Z}} & \Delta\\
\Delta & -\tilde{\epsilon}_{k}+\tilde{V}_{\text{Z}}
\end{array}\right)
\]

\end_inset

reads as
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\mathcal{H}}_{\text{BdG}}=\boldsymbol{\mathcal{U}}\boldsymbol{\mathcal{E}}\boldsymbol{\mathcal{U}}^{\dagger}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\mathcal{E}}$
\end_inset

 being the diagonal matrix of eigenenergies 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{k\pm}=\tilde{V}_{\text{Z}}\pm\sqrt{\Delta^{2}+\tilde{\epsilon}_{k}^{2}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\mathcal{U}}$
\end_inset

 the transformation built from the (normalized) eigenvectors 
\begin_inset Formula $(u_{k\pm},\,v_{k\pm})$
\end_inset

, meaning 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{k\sigma}=u_{k}c_{k\sigma}+v_{k}^{*}c_{-k\bar{\sigma}}^{\dagger}$
\end_inset

.
