) through the expression of the eigenvectors using 
\emph on
Mathematica
\emph default
, the self-consistent gap equation with Zeeman 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta=U\rho_{\uparrow\downarrow}^{\text{eh}}$
\end_inset

 reads explicitly as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\Delta= & -U\sum_{k}\frac{\Delta}{4\tilde{E}_{k}}\left[\tanh\left(\frac{\tilde{V}_{\text{Z}}+\tilde{E}_{k}}{2k_{B}T}\right)-\tanh\left(\frac{\tilde{V}_{\text{Z}}-\tilde{E}_{k}}{2k_{B}T}\right)\right]
\end{align*}

\end_inset

As necessary, ignoring 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{V}_{\text{Z}}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta V_{\text{Z}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta\mu$
\end_inset

 this reduces to the traditional gap equation in Eq.(
\begin_inset Formula $\text{\ref{eq:gapeq}}$
\end_inset

).
 Note that this has a nonzero solution only if the interaction is attractive
 i.e 
\begin_inset Formula $U<0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To obtain the self-consistent equations for the induced Zeeman 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta V_{\text{Z}}$
\end_inset

 and chemical potential 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta\mu$
\end_inset

 through Eq.(
\begin_inset Formula $\text{\ref{eq:gapeqs}}$
\end_inset

)(right) we follow the same treatment.
 These are obtained by expressing the correlations in terms of the Bogoliubov
 basis, reading
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\rho_{\uparrow\uparrow}^{\text{ee}}=\frac{1}{N}\sum_{k}\left[|u_{k+}|^{2}f(E_{k+})+|u_{k-}|f(E_{k-})\right]
\]

\end_inset

and similarly for 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{\downarrow\downarrow}^{\text{ee}}$
\end_inset

 but with flipped sign of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{\text{Z}}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

